	<title>Questions</title>
<introduction>This section considers the main clause and embedded clause varieties of Yes/No questions and content questions.  In English, main clause Yes/No questions are formed by moving an auxiliary verb in front of the subject.  Other languages use a Yes/No question marker word or particle or special complementizer instead of the fronted auxiliary.  This is the case in embedded Yes/No questions in English; no auxiliary fronting is allowed but <example>whether</example> or <example>if</example> fills the complementizer position.<br/><br/>
X-bar theory takes the complementizer to be the head of the phrase, so a CP sits on top of the IP for questions.  Sample trees for main clause and embedded Yes/No questions in English are shown here.
